text:
This situation reminds me of the Aluthgama incident in Sri Lanka, where false rumors were spread claiming that Muslim-owned restaurants were using chemicals to make people infertile. It‚Äôs a tactic that appears to be repeating itself in Kashmir‚Äîdriven by politically motivated misinformation. In the Sri Lankan case, a Buddhist monk, Ayagama Samitha, and his driver were allegedly attacked by Muslims in Dharga Town, sparking mob violence against Muslim businesses‚Äîsimilar to what‚Äôs happening in Kashmir now.

Buddhist figures like Yana Sara were reportedly used to spread false narratives, just as religious figures in India are being used today to incite communal tensions. Media outlets like Hiru TV in Sri Lanka played a role in amplifying this misinformation‚Äîagain, a parallel to how some Indian media outlets operate today.

Shockingly, it was later revealed that the individuals accused of being Muslims in the Sri Lankan incident weren‚Äôt even Muslim. There‚Äôs a documentary about this case that uncovers these truths. At the time, Rajapaksa, who was close to Modi, was in power. There are claims that similar strategies were used to justify violence, including church bo*bings blamed on Muslims, all contributing to the 2022 riots.

In conclusion, these events appear to be politically orchestrated, using religion and misinformation as tools to provoke unrest.
